1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:03,192
In 1912, fragments from a gravel pit

2
00:00:03,192 --> 00:00:06,897
in Sussex seemed to give British science

3
00:00:06,897 --> 00:00:08,750
the fossil it wanted.

4
00:00:08,750 --> 00:00:11,692
A human-like skull. An ape-like jaw.

5
00:00:11,692 --> 00:00:14,090
A famous name: Piltdown Man.

6
00:00:15,201 --> 00:00:17,292
The evidence was thin, but the story

7
00:00:17,292 --> 00:00:20,876
was powerful. It fit a brain-first theory,

8
00:00:20,876 --> 00:00:23,594
and gave Britain its own ancient ancestor.

9
00:00:24,435 --> 00:00:27,111
Some anatomists doubted the skull and jaw

10
00:00:27,111 --> 00:00:29,788
belonged together. But access was limited,

11
00:00:29,788 --> 00:00:32,388
prestige was heavy, and the specimen kept

12
00:00:32,388 --> 00:00:35,432
circulating as authority. The fraud was

13
00:00:35,432 --> 00:00:37,435
not perfect. It was welcome.

14
00:00:38,417 --> 00:00:42,323
By 1953, tests exposed the trick.

15
00:00:42,323 --> 00:00:44,189
The skull was recent human bone.

16
00:00:44,993 --> 00:00:46,537
The jaw was from an orangutan.

17
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:48,505
The teeth had been filed.

18
00:00:49,106 --> 00:00:50,392
The bones had been stained.

19
00:00:51,113 --> 00:00:53,234
The hoax survived because it let the

20
00:00:53,234 --> 00:00:56,353
field feel correct. The mystery fades.

21
00:00:56,975 --> 00:00:58,320
The receipts remain.
